Analyzing Macroeconomic Trends with Aurora

Introduction

The aurora package allows you to easily fetch and align disparate data sourcesweather, economics, and eventsinto a single daily timeline.

Usage

source('../R/aurora.R')

Fetching Data

You can fetch a comprehensive dataset for a specific location and date range. Here we look at Ottawa, Canada for 1st January, 2025 to 1st December, 2025.

# Fetches data from Open-Meteo, FRED, and GDELT
data <- get_macroeconomic_data(
  start_date = "2025-01-01",
  end_date   = "2025-12-01",
  latitude   = 55.6761, 
  longitude  = 12.5683
)

Add revenue to dataframe

Once you have the data, you can easily add your revenue column to the dataframe.

rev_data <- revenue_merge(data,"../Scripts/revenue_data_2025.csv")

Generate plots

You can generate plots of each feature vs revenue on given timeline for trend analysis.

plots = c("avg_temp", "max_temp", "tot_rain", "natural_disaster_score", "political_unrest_score","interest_rate","mortgage_rate", "unemployment", "cpi_inflation","gdp", "public_debt")

plotter(rev_data,
          cols = plots,
          date_col = "Date",
          revenue_col = "Revenue",
          ncol = 3,
          scale_method = "zscore")
